[13:46] <lizmat> So I've created two optimized versions of .subst in https://raku.land/zef:lizmat/String::Utils#replace   "replace" and "replace-all"

[13:46] <lizmat> which are up to 8x as fast as the equivalent .subst statement

[13:47] <lizmat> cause: no Match object creation, and no $/ setting

[13:48] <lizmat> I think we cannot change the behaviour of .subst regarding setting of $/, because it would cause too much breakage in the ecosystem

[13:48] <lizmat> but I was thinking of creating an updated .subst method in 6.e called .replace

[13:49] <lizmat> which would probably allow to keep a good deal of the performance improvement that the stripped down versions in String::Utils provide

[14:16] <lizmat> hmmm..  seems like a discovered an ancient artefact:   who knows what the command-line option "parsetrace" is supposed to do?

[14:17] <lizmat> rakkable: eco-provides parsetrace

[14:17] <rakkable> lizmat, Running: eco-provides parsetrace, please be patient!

[14:17] <rakkable> lizmat, No occurrences found for: eco-provides parsetrace

[14:27] <ShimmerFairy> I don't actually know, but that sure sounds like a `use Grammar::Tracer` analogue to me. A quick partial look through git blame on NQP shows that it's been around since the time NQP was partially handwritten PIR. (Seems to have mapped to a "rxtrace" named arg?)

[14:31] <ShimmerFairy> lizmat: NQP commit 2cd14a327163c7c337c2f5ea47ab8eb70232ffc8 is where --parsetrace was introduced, back in late 2009. Seems to have enabled calling method DEBUG on a Cursor immediately after !cursor_init, and before the "regex" method (presumably ran the actual parsing steps)

[14:31] <ShimmerFairy> (with said DEBUG method having been introduced in some earlier commit)

[14:59] <ShimmerFairy> I'm not 100% on this, but after looking around it seems that --parsetrace was added to NQP::Compiler, which likely ceased to function on the move to QRegex (I don't the equivalent DEBUG code was ever there). Later on, --rxtrace was added to HLL::Compiler. Eventually that option was removed, with its commit noting that --target=parse exposes (mostly?) the same info.

[15:00] <ShimmerFairy> So in short, without stepping into a time machine to resurrect Parrot, I think --parsetrace is ultimately an early form of --target=parse that slipped through the cracks when things were NQP-ified.

